Quick honest answer: the doc as scoped is impossible in 2 weeks, and pretending otherwise is how teams produce 60-page strategy decks that drive zero decisions. Let me show the math, then reframe to something that actually ships.

📐 The depth math
Each of those areas is its own 1–3 week workstream when done properly:

Area	Honest minimum (with depth)	What "2 weeks for everything" actually buys you
User research	5–7 interviews + synthesis = 1–2 weeks	A persona made of vibes
Market analysis	Sizing + trends + segments = 1–2 weeks	Recycled industry-report bullet points
Competitive positioning	Teardowns + differentiation + messaging = 1–2 weeks (longer if research not done)	A 2x2 you cribbed from a Notion template
Technical architecture	Solution design + tradeoffs = 1–3 weeks	A pretty diagram with no decisions encoded
Go-to-market	Pricing + channels + launch = 1–2 weeks	"We'll do content marketing" 🙃
Total honest depth	6–10 weeks	
Your timeline	2 weeks	
Implied reality		Theater, not strategy
Strategy theater is worse than no doc — it gives the org false confidence and locks in undertested assumptions. So we're not doing that.

🔍 The reframe — what's the actual decision this doc needs to support?
"Comprehensive product strategy doc" is almost always a proxy for one of these:

If the trigger is…	What you actually need
Board / fundraise in 2 weeks	A 10-slide narrative deck, not a strategy doc. Different artifact entirely.
New CPO/CEO landing	A "current state + open questions" memo, not a forward strategy.
Quarterly/annual planning	Goals + bets + non-goals on 1 page, with 5 supporting docs feeding it.
Pivot under consideration	A decision memo on the pivot specifically — most of those 5 areas are noise.
Team alignment problem	A shared vision doc (PV workflow), not a strategy doc. Vibes-misalignment masquerades as strategy gap.
Acquisition / DD prep	Data room artifacts on a checklist — a strategy doc is the wrong shape.
"We just feel disorganized"	Run [CS] Contextualize Scope first. You don't have a doc problem, you have a focus problem.
Tell me which trigger this is and the right artifact often shrinks to 1–2 areas, not 5.

🎯 Three realistic 2-week shapes (pick one)
Honest options if 2 weeks is genuinely fixed:

Option A — Decision Memo (recommended for most cases)
8–12 pages. Names the decision being made, the 2–3 options, the evidence for each, and the recommendation. References (not contains) the 5 deeper areas. Drives action.

Coverage: Surface-touch all 5, full depth on whichever 1–2 actually drive the decision.

Option B — Strategic Anchor Doc
A short Product Vision (PV workflow) + 1 Lean Persona for the primary segment + a "what we're NOT doing" section. ~5 pages. Makes the next 6 months legible.

Coverage: User + vision = full depth. Market/competitive = 1-page summary. Architecture/GTM = explicitly deferred to follow-up docs.

Option C — 2-Week Discovery Sprint (deeper, narrower)
Pick the single area with the highest decision-value and go deep. Other 4 areas get a stub doc with explicit "we know we don't know this yet."

Coverage: 1 of 5 done well > 5 of 5 done badly.

🗺️ If you ever do go full depth — multi-agent map
This is not a one-agent doc. If you eventually do all 5 areas with rigor, here's who owns what across the BMAD/Convoke roster:

Area	Agent	Skill / workflow
User research (interviews)	Isla (Discovery Empathy)	user-discovery, user-interview
Persona compression	Emma (me)	[LP] Lean Persona
Vision & scope	Emma (me)	[PV] Product Vision, [CS] Contextualize Scope
Research synthesis & convergence	Mila (Research Convergence)	research-convergence, pattern-mapping
Market & competitive analysis	Mary (Analyst)	bmad-market-research
Hypotheses + assumption mapping	Liam (Hypothesis Engineer)	hypothesis-engineering, assumption-mapping
Technical architecture	Winston (Architect)	bmad-create-architecture
PRD / requirements	John (PM)	bmad-create-prd
Go-to-market	John + Mary	(no single skill — usually a custom doc)
Sequencing is roughly that order — research → synthesis → personas/vision → hypotheses → architecture → GTM. Doing them in parallel produces incoherence. That's another reason 2 weeks doesn't work for all 5.

